76561198052032850,Recommended,263200,10700955,"Posted: 23 June, 2014",all,bounding star,Fantastic game with intuitive and original mechanics and lots of neat ideas. Deserves a lot more attention from fans
,Recommended,263200,31581195,Posted: 6 May,all,Droopy The Dog,"Signs of life is an absolutely fantastic find and I'm lucky I gave it a chance.I've tried a lot of the various terraria successors on steam. From the dumpster fire that was Edge of Space, to the mild interest followed by long periods of boredom that was Starbound. They've invariably been disapointments.Except for Signs of Life. I've binged it over the last few days and enjoyed it immensely--=Warning, mild spoilers ahead, no secrets outright blown, but I'm going to illustrate lots of general possibilities you might otherwise have to learn about yourself in game=--It does the basics incredibly well.The combat is very good! The best in the genre, well above Terraria standards. There's locational damage and armour ratings for every enemy, the enemies actually have multiple varied attacks and a good chunk of personality. Combat rewards lateral thinking incredibly well, there's one particular mechanical enemy you can use your crafting tools and an electical interface to disable rather than destroy directly. Although destroying directly is definitely an option, the most obvious one infact.The bosses are great too, there's not many yet, but the ones that there are are lovingly well made. There's a real Monster Hunter feel to them, where you tend to tear them apart piece by piece, dissabling and enabling new attacks on the way, and depending on how you cut them down you get different loot to craft unique new weapons. There's one particularly slimy boss that must have 16 different destrucible elements of, which makes for a fun variety of ways to take it out. (And packing high-explosives especially satisfying).The mining is satisfying in speed and constantly upgraded as you go, and the different various options you have make it less than mindless thankfully. And the generated cave systems are expansive enough that you can spelunk around and mine the much quicker ultra-rich deposit props. Downward exploration can get be a real chore to return from in the very early game, but you get lots of tools to make vertical traversal a doddle later on.Game performance is great, no stupidly long loading times or frame hitches or issues with large numbers of objects on screen. Not much else to say, but in comparison to some other titles, it blows them out of the water.And what's more it does things a little differently and miraculously it well too.The procedural stuff, I cannot emphasise it enough! Enemies are suceptible to friendly fire and environmental damage. Mining with explosives is a little more detailed than normal, it doesn't just blow up blocks in a set area, they travel further in soft materials than hard ones, and damages the the layers underneath those blown clean-off to make excavating them much easier too. You don't just automatically suck things up around you, you can either manually pick them up with your cursor or use the little tractor gun built into your tool to grab things around you, but if you move quick enough the momentum will send the item sailing past you, and if that was something like an egg it will splatter on the nearest wall, and if it was a rock or an arrow, it's now a damaging projective. I was so impressed to discover that as I upgraded my tool I was even able to to litterally pluck enemy incoming projectiles out of the air to be fire right back at them. And with the critical damage locations built into the enemies, the procedural animations make melee combat much more entertaining, stepping and aiming just the right way and doing a thrust into just the right place is much more entertaining than just swinging wildly. The detail in everything is just sublime.The UI, in keeping with the game, is incredibly procedural. Storage containers aren't cells they're just contiguous spaces you can spread your items out in, a la the old Ultima VII/Ultima Online style. With the much needed auto-sort fuction button built into the game to spread everything out evenly, thank god. Storage containers don't mean much on their own, but that approach to everything makes the game so much more immersive. You don't just drop power cores on your high tech machinery, you open them up and drop them into the power socket. You aquire some unkown alien artifacts, and instead of getting a ""You don't know how to use this yet"" dialogue, it shows you the surface covered in strange symbols that you can search for clues in and spin dials on until you get it to work. It works fantastically well to make you really think about things in a less ""gamey"" way.The game rewards, and in fact requires, so much lateral thinking to solve all the little mysteries hand crafted into the otherwise proceedural world. There's the sealed human craft and facilities built into the surface, which are impervious to your lower upgrade level mining tools, but you can enter yourself much sooner by a little exploration and unconventional tool-use. Then there's the alien artifacts, which you have to go full xeno-acheologist to figure out. You don't just find a magical alien rosetta stone and can suddenly read everything, you have to examine the symbols across various sites and figure out their meaning, and test out your theories until something finally works. Even throwing food to distract wild enemies is fun.Ok, so that a lot of gushing. Time for the reality check, here's the bad:The AI, it isn't bad, but nothing groundbreaking. Which in a game where it's possible to quickly build fortifications on the fly, makes it easy to game the basic enemy types. If you put yourself just out of reach, they'll keep impotently attacking beneath you, and pretty much everything can be neutered by boxing them in dirt, then mining a tiny hole to stab them through. The boss AIs work a little better at this, with either terrain ignoring or terrain destroying attacks to make them more difficult to box in.Content, it got some obvious gaps still and a couple of placeholders. It's not bare at all, but after a little cheating with the built in dev-tools I think I've basically seen all there is for now.Lighting, it's annoyingly dark at times whilst you're mining, the built in light on your tool is exceedingly weak, even when upgraded, as are the basic torches. In retrospect I probably should have used the flare gun more often as there's not much else to use sap for, but I wasn't sure if I might need it for something later in the tech tree. Which meant I spent a lot of time underground barely able to see a few blocks ahead and naviagting by the scanning laser and the minimap.So my opinion overall is very positive. Signs of Life still has room to grow in content, but what there is is brilliant, and the quality of the game mechanically and the polish of some of the content already put in fills me with confidence that further content will be top quality. And even in the few days I've owned the game I've seen multiple posts by the dev's responding to players and teasing future updates, so I'm not worried about abandonment either. The only other early access game I've been anywhere near as pleased with is Starsector, which has been the gold standard for me.So if you like 2D exploration/combat/survival games, get it. It's got some great gameplay and at $10 it's worth it even as-is, so no early access remorse to haunt you."
76561198026701476,Recommended,263200,14215518,"Posted: 28 January, 2015",all,Onikage-056,"Compared to other games I've played, Signs of Life is both more simplistic, and more complex. Simpler in that construction of a base doesn't take 5 days, and that hordes of enemies are, while a possibility, not likely to simply turn into a never-ending swarm that'll override any defensive measures in a couple minutes.The complexity comes from the mid and late-game (for now) crafting, where you need to use literally every crafting station/system you have on hand to build things like the rocket launcher or the Jewel Bow. Even some of the earlier recipes can take 4 or 5 differing components to make, and at least 2 crafting stations to make the parts in the first place.Honestly, I don't find it a problem. I find it a nice change of pace from the more ""grind it til you have it"" tendency of more than a few other games (World of Warcraft, for example.).My only real issues stem from just how much digging you're apt to do just to get enough resources to build that fancy Material Printer or that last box of rockets.I would rate this game a 9/10 as it is, if only because the game is incomplete."
