,Recommended,263200,20361545,"Posted: 6 January, 2016",all,IraenShift,"If you played Terraria or Starbound, then you'll feel right at home here.  The mechanics are pretty similar with the occasional tweak here and there. There's a fairly typical mix of old and new weapons, swords vs guns and so on. It's nice that to have an early armor options that require minimal killing of things, although some of the plants can be deadly, since some of the critters that drop leather are kinda dangerous.At this point (0.6?) the limited story is a bit of a downside in my opinion. It feels disconnected, kind of like my experience in Starbound up to the initial starbase and thereabouts. Terraria has a stronger, but looser narrative. I think it'd be nice to tie the player in a bit more, since whatever the lore is aside, it feels like the player crash landed and then stumbled into stuff. So, there's not much attachment or concern for the back story people except to hope they had some good stuff you can loot and take not of any warnings about what to avoid... Not sure why I've crashed on a planet in an escape pod.Regarding the UI:I do think that the inventory is not a strong point as is. It's interesting, but stuff visually overlaps, which is a little annoying when you have to click on things and having to manually request auto-arrange/auto-sort can be annoying at times. The auto-bar which groups items into a small set of categories and provides access via scroll to all items of a certain type through a particular bar is, however, a nifty feature, even if it occasionally leads to unintended shooting (you know, like of your foot!) and food consumption... One of the more interesting notions is how the map works. You don't get a map by default or even by passive exploration, you've got to actively build one with the scanner. I'd strongly recommend upgrading it at least one step before engaging in a serious world mapping attempt, though, it'll make it a fair bit easier.TL;DRFun to play and fairly engaging, but there's not pressure to build anything more than a minimal shelter before heading off to explore. The AI communications are annoying in a way, but a nice touch even if it's kinda of telling you that you're an idiot the entire time and implying that you wouldn't even survive without it's help. Some things to get used to with the user interface (UI) and movement. Also, try not to fall too far, it's kind of painful.P.S.Giant Robot Chicken is a plus. Surprised that it's peaceful if you don't attack it though. Might be funny if there was a base in the game somewhere that looked like the chicken gave it a hard time..."
