,Not Recommended,263200,20533896,"Posted: 14 January, 2016",all,Stungun,"Version reviewed: 0.6.I understand this is early access, but I was still expecting a lot more from this game. A few things in the trailer don't seem to exist in the current version of the game (e.g. starting in a base, a jump-jet with unlimited fuel, a moon environment... it actually looks like the early parts of the trailer... that's supposed to be backstory, but presenting it in the form of actual gameplay that we the players don't get to experience is a dirty trick. Though there is still a very playable (if incomplete) game here with most of the demonstrated features. I still, though, have other criticisms.First of all, the inventory management system is a serious pain. With no auto-organizing, optional snap-to-grid placements, and the inefficent sort/organize functions for containers... at least being able to carry an unlimited number of nested containers and label them though, helps organize things. But something tells me the final version of the game is going to do away with that.Secondly, the controls. In addition to the difficulty of successfully picking up smaller/thinner items, there's also the awkward and clumsy movement that gives me lots of frustration trying to make jumps. It's also hard to attack exactly where you want to attack. Singling out the right item you want to use in automatic mode takes a long time if you've got a lot of stuff (and an effective unlimited inventory means you can and should get as many toys on your person as possible) and manual mode is impractical since the hotbar is limited to seven slots plus two quick slots.Thirdly is the fake difficulty. Death is cheap (you drop everything and respawn, and I don't think items ever disappear from the world) but it can be really irritating to get back to where you dropped all your stuff -- especially when you respawn with a partial bar of health, an empty stomach (you only regenerate health when you've had something to eat), and no armor. And many monsters that stand in your way can kill you in precisely two hits in that state. And then there's the frustration of having to re-organize your main inventory -- since whenever you pick something up with the grab laser (the fastest way to pick stuff up) it just gets thrown into a random spot in your bag.Fourth -- the progression. It just doesn't feel right. This is clearly a space-age survival game, but the metals available to use don't even include titanium. Steel is the second-best metal there is, with the tier after that being practical post-game equipment. Also, why the heck is bronze stronger than iron?Fifth, everything that's missing. No music. No way to quickly switch ammo types on a held weapon (you need to select the item in question which you probably have in a nested container in your inventory to change its used ammo).  No mechanism wiring systems (no designing elaborate traps or light switches). No liquids (water/lava/etc).I haven't even tried to build a base of my own because the game gives you a prefabricated base from the start, and building structures is made a lot more complicated than it has to be as every building material has like 8 different types of blocks, and the clunky interface and crafting required would make it more of a chore than it's worth. I dread having to build anything creatively in this game.I've clocked 31 hours into this game (as of this writing) and I feel like I've basically seen everything there is to see. That's depressingly low for a survival game. You're better off going for Starbound -- this game has a long way to go before it can even hold a candle to it.Maybe I'll check back in a few versions and see how it's advanced."
76561198037018029,Recommended,263200,13263248,"Posted: 6 December, 2014",all,Biowolf80,I go around flinging dung at the wild life 10/10 would fling it again
76561198006889979,Not Recommended,263200,20649025,"Posted: 20 January, 2016",all,Pops,"Steam recommended this one.  I bought it because it seemed like Starbound, both in graphical style and in game content.  But as it usually is on Steam, let the buyer beware.  Because this game is a frustrating mess that anyone would be better to avoid.At first glance, the game is pretty and detailed - graphically the game works...however...Altho the game doesnt state it, this is a digging game.  You dig...and dig...and dig.  The game only progresses when you dig.  It slows the game down to a boring crawl.  Can't make steel until you find anthracite...and that one is VERY far underground.  Funny thing - you can build a laser pistol, but you cant make steel.Combat just plain ole sucks.   Weaponry, when you can make something useful,  is laughably  underpowered.  Three shots from a pistol to kill a crawling slug,  anything bigger and you better be climbing...if you get caught on a straight run, you're dead.  Not because you dont have something that will do the job - you just can't access it fast enough in the clunky UI before the monsters kill you.Crafting recipes, while seeming to be balanced, hit an invisible wall because of two things: a required ""Project"" and the correct materials.  Recipes show up based on what you pick up, meaning that you may get a recipe you can't use, because you're not sure what the resource is from.   Add in that you may have the materials, but can't use a recipe because you can't complete a required Project, and frustration ensues.Also, prepare to restart again and again...with nothing.  When you die, and you WILL die because of the poor game mechanics, you drop everything you own.  Everything...right down to your sandals.   Then you get restarted back on the surface sans anything.  Which means totally resupplying yourself and a long run back to where you died to reclaim all your swag before you can try anything else....which is totally unecessary and totally boring.  And of course you can't build anything to help with the restart process because the resources are too rare.  Catch-22.  For me, that was the thing which made the game more trouble than it was worth.Go spend your ten bucks on something else..stay away from this one."
